    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Tech-driven transformation and global shift in perspectives are changing educational landscapes worldwide, and history classes in the US are a prime example. There's a strong, vocal push from some media and marginalized groups favoring identity politics and critical race theory over traditional teaching to foreground various experiences, particularly those of oppressed minorities.\n\nOpponents argue this diverts from the objective historical narrative and patriotism, insisting that it's more about political motives than genuine educational reform. Skeptics say it marginalizes classic American values and experiences and creates social division.\n\nHowever, what defines this as truly negative is deeply subjective and a divisive debate. Proponents hail it as necessary to correct historical oversights, and provide marginalized groups' perspectives while opponents regard it as threatening to national unity and cultural traditions. Technological advancements are compelling societies to adapt their learning systems to foster critical thinking and an inclusive worldview, thus shaping history classes to be more representative of the changing global context.",
